<content type="html" xml:base="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=5879&amp;p=54447#p54447"><![CDATA[
Yeah, seriously, when I see how much I can fit into the limited amount of memory on the NES, I can't believe how much modern games use. It seems like many games just waste so much RAM, but then again they have a lot more information to process than your typical NES game. They probably can get away with it too since so much more is available. For example, they may find it quicker to dedicate an entire byte to a status flag, rather than using each individual bit. And since they can get away with it anyways, they probably don't care. Maybe I'm wrong though; I haven't programmed for modern systems ever.<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=138">Celius</a> — Sun Dec 27, 2009 2:07 am</p><hr />
]]></content>
